# Layout: Structure Before CSS

Before fixing any layout or positioning issue, read the HTML structure first.

## Rule
Never apply hardcoded pixel offsets (e.g. `top: 44px`) to solve a layout problem without first checking whether a structural HTML change would be more robust.

## Pattern to follow

1. Read the relevant HTML to understand the element hierarchy
2. Ask: can a wrapper element solve this without needing to know any sizes?
3. If yes — use the wrapper. If no — use a CSS custom property, not a magic number.

## Examples

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD: guessing the topbar height -->
.tab-bar { position: sticky; top: 44px; }

<!-- ✅ GOOD: wrap both elements so they stick together -->
<div class="sticky-header">      <!-- position: sticky; top: 0 -->
  <div class="topbar">…</div>
  <div class="tab-bar">…</div>
</div>
```

If a pixel value is truly unavoidable, define it as a CSS custom property on `:root` so it has one source of truth:

```css
:root { --topbar-height: 44px; }
.tab-bar { top: var(--topbar-height); }
```
